    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Nuclear Plant in the Neighborhood</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Wright Salisbury letter contends nuclear power is solution to energy problems (April 26 William Sweet Op-Ed article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Kudos to William Sweet for ''The Nuclear Option.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Kudos to William Sweet for ''The Nuclear Option.''</p>
        <p>Recently, I had dinner with two engineers and mentioned that the solution to our energy problems was atomic energy. They practically fell on my neck weeping. One said he had long ago stopped discussing atomic energy because of the shocked silences it evoked.</p>
        <p>After the Chernobyl explosion and the Three Mile Island accident, atomic energy has become verboten. France generates 80 percent of its electricity with atomic energy.</p>
        <p>The only solution to our energy problems that is workable at present is atomic energy. It's clean, and the only problem is the storing of the waste, which, though problematic, is not nearly as problematic as the large amounts of carbon dioxide emitted into our atmosphere by coal and oil.</p>
        <p>Wright Salisbury  Lexington, Mass., April 26, 2006</p>
      </block>
